history: Uhl-Gee is named after general Uhl-Gee-Moon-Dock, who successfully defended Korea against a Tang's invasion force of nearly one million soldiers led by Yang-Jay in the year six-hundred-twelve A.D.. Uhl-Gee, employing hit-and-run guerrilla tactics, was able to decimate a large percentage of the force. The diagram represents his surname. The forty-two movements represent the author's age when he designed the pattern.
